{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real filesystem watching scope/recursion, triggered by placing a real file under a real subdirectory. MOCK-MISS: this is not just parser logic; it is watcher-to-pipeline handoff from OS events. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: in-process event stubs can miss platform watcher behavior (recursive watch semantics), so System is needed. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: none.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp input/output directory tree, create a nested subdirectory, write a file into it, and assert exactly one transformed output is produced for that nested file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Minimum failure boundary is module interaction (request ingestion -> dedupe window state -> pipeline dispatch). INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) no required real OS/network/subprocess in behavior text; requests can be injected in-process, so System is rejected. (b) no AI output dependency. (c) no multi-agent sequence. (d) no LLM stage handoff. REJECTION-GATE (higher level rejected): behavior text says 'second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window' and does not require real filesystem event characteristics.","test_description":"Wire real dedupe + scheduler/dispatcher modules with a controllable clock, submit two identical path requests within the configured window, and assert only one dispatch to the transformation pipeline occurs; submit after window expiry and assert dispatch occurs again.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on OS event emission patterns ('operating system emits multiple filesystem events'). REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: mocked watcher callbacks can trivially pass and hide real duplicate-event bursts/coalescing differences. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: none.","test_description":"Run daemon with a real watched directory and perform a write pattern known to trigger multiple FS notifications (e.g., temp-write+rename or chunked write) on the host OS; assert one and only one processing/output artifact for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is OS filesystem lifecycle (directory deletion/recreation, inode replacement) plus live watcher reattachment. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: in-process fakes cannot faithfully reproduce watcher invalidation/rebind behavior across real directory replacement. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: none.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real directory, delete the watched directory while running, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file and assert it is processed without restarting the daemon process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Ordering depends on real file creation timestamp behavior and near-simultaneous arrival timing from OS/filesystem. MOCK-MISS: this is cross-module ordering under real metadata/event timing, not just local sort logic. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: synthetic timestamps/events can hide platform timestamp resolution and race behavior. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: none.","test_description":"With daemon running on a real watched directory, create multiple files in rapid succession (or controlled parallel writes), capture observed processing order, and assert it matches each file's filesystem creation timestamp ordering as read by the daemon logic.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real concurrent write behavior and OS watcher timing (arrival before file is stable). REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: mocked writes/events usually do not reproduce partial-write visibility, buffering, and stabilization timing issues. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: none.","test_description":"Run daemon on a real directory, begin writing a large file in chunks with delays so arrival fires early, verify no processing starts during active writes, then verify processing starts only after final chunk/close completes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
